WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.680
Welcome, everyone, to the webinar on sharing on short notice, where we'll show you how

00:00:10.680 --> 00:00:15.000
to get your teaching materials online with R Markdown.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:19.840
So, hello, we're really happy you could join us today.

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:23.559
We know that everybody has a lot of things going on, so we appreciate you taking the

00:00:23.559 --> 00:00:27.240
time to join us this afternoon.

00:00:27.240 --> 00:00:34.279
My name is Allison Hill, and I'm a data scientist and professional educator at RStudio.

00:00:34.279 --> 00:00:38.759
And I'm Desirée De Leon, and I interned with Allison last summer at RStudio on the

00:00:38.759 --> 00:00:41.599
education team.

00:00:41.599 --> 00:00:44.799
And even though we don't have a video feed in this webinar, we promise we are real-life

00:00:44.799 --> 00:00:52.119
humans who are also stuck at home just now, like you all, sitting in front of our computers.

00:00:52.119 --> 00:00:56.119
And one thing that Desirée and I both have in common is that we ship a lot of websites.

00:00:56.160 --> 00:01:01.560
I'm a developmental psychologist, Desirée is a neuroscientist, neither of us is a web

00:01:01.560 --> 00:01:06.879
developer, but we both ship a lot of websites for teaching data science.

00:01:06.879 --> 00:01:09.720
And here are just a few of them.

00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:20.480
If you type the short link on the bottom of our slides, it's rstd.io forward slash sharing,

00:01:20.480 --> 00:01:22.919
you'll be able to see our slides and follow along in your browser.

00:01:23.160 --> 00:01:26.440
So you can see all of these links are also clickable for you.

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:31.639
Each of these sites was built using R Markdown with different tools chosen depending on what

00:01:31.639 --> 00:01:32.639
we needed.

00:01:32.639 --> 00:01:34.639
So that's us.

00:01:34.639 --> 00:01:37.559
Who are you?

00:01:37.559 --> 00:01:40.279
We think you're an educator.

00:01:40.279 --> 00:01:44.720
And you have R Markdown files that you use for teaching.

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:48.559
But they may be stuck on your computer, and you need to share them easily with others

00:01:48.559 --> 00:01:51.680
without filling up their inboxes.

00:01:51.680 --> 00:01:55.959
And that's because you probably have a new classroom space that looks like this.

00:01:55.959 --> 00:02:01.199
So sharing needs to be done 100% online.

00:02:01.199 --> 00:02:06.160
And you might feel like this right now, everything seems to need your attention, but you cannot

00:02:06.160 --> 00:02:07.160
do everything.

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:14.800
So with that in mind, today, we'd like to give you a quick tour of the R Markdown tools

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:23.279
that you can use to get your course materials online on very short notice.

00:02:23.279 --> 00:02:27.440
We'll show you how to build a course website to help you teach and reach learners using

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:29.399
R Markdown and friends.

00:02:29.399 --> 00:02:34.800
And our goal is to give you a quick boost to help you get your site up off the ground

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:40.199
with a shareable link so that you can get on with your teaching and hopefully avoid

00:02:40.199 --> 00:02:43.479
crashing in the process.

00:02:43.479 --> 00:02:45.600
So why make a course website at all?

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:49.839
I think of it as a way, first, to help me organize my own stuff, to get all my piles

00:02:49.839 --> 00:02:52.759
of teaching documents into some kind of order.

00:02:52.759 --> 00:02:56.160
And that makes it more reproducible for myself and for others.

00:02:56.160 --> 00:02:58.679
But it's also a way to make my teaching more resilient.

00:02:58.679 --> 00:03:03.559
If I'm organized and online, I can be more nimble when changes need to happen.

00:03:03.559 --> 00:03:06.759
And a side benefit of all that is that it also makes it more shareable.

00:03:06.759 --> 00:03:12.199
So it makes it easier for learners, too, because they see what I see.

00:03:12.199 --> 00:03:14.440
So we'll be building websites with R Markdown.

00:03:14.440 --> 00:03:18.839
And because of that, we'll start by talking about building a single R Markdown file.

00:03:18.839 --> 00:03:20.839
So Desiree, you're up.

00:03:20.839 --> 00:03:21.839
All right.

00:03:21.839 --> 00:03:23.080
Thanks, Allison.

00:03:23.080 --> 00:03:25.800
So let's see.

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:31.440
Jumping right in, what does an R Markdown file look like?

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:35.880
So here's an R project folder for a lab, let's say.

00:03:35.880 --> 00:03:39.440
And inside that folder, you'll notice an R project file.

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:45.720
And opening that file in RStudio takes us here, where we can see our single R Markdown

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:46.720
file.

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:51.600
And as I mentioned, this is one for a lab that's going to visualize data from the Museum

00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:52.600
of Modern Art.

00:03:52.600 --> 00:03:57.240
So let's just quickly walk through some of the key parts of this file.

00:03:57.240 --> 00:04:02.399
It starts with metadata written in YAML, which is a list of keys on the left and their values

00:04:02.399 --> 00:04:04.440
on the right.

00:04:04.440 --> 00:04:12.000
And the first key you see is title, which is, in this case, Lab 02 MoMA Museum Tour.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.000
And the last section is all about output in the YAML.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.160
So here, the output is an HTML document.

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:25.119
And beneath that, we can add options to our HTML document, for example, a table of contents

00:04:25.119 --> 00:04:29.359
with the key TOC set to true.

00:04:29.359 --> 00:04:31.559
So that's the metadata.

00:04:31.679 --> 00:04:37.760
But the real meat in your R Markdown file is text written in Markdown and, of course,

00:04:37.760 --> 00:04:44.399
code written in R. So these three things, metadata, text, and code, make up an R Markdown

00:04:44.399 --> 00:04:45.399
document.

00:04:45.399 --> 00:04:54.679
So, of course, Desiree, the real magic happens when you click on the knit button and see

00:04:54.679 --> 00:04:59.720
your file turned into HTML.

00:04:59.720 --> 00:05:05.519
So when we click on the knit button, we can watch the build happening in the bottom pane.

00:05:05.519 --> 00:05:08.000
Our Markdown document gets processed.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.920
And you can see the rendered HTML file locally.

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:17.200
You can also choose to open it up in a bigger browser and explore around by clicking on

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:21.799
it, testing a few things out.

00:05:22.799 --> 00:05:26.760
Okay.

00:05:26.760 --> 00:05:30.959
So here's a screenshot of what we just showed you, what we knit.

00:05:30.959 --> 00:05:35.760
And we can see that using the theme key in our YAML, we were able to apply changes to

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:38.320
our fonts and colors.

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:43.679
And we have this nice table of contents that's floating off to the side.

00:05:43.679 --> 00:05:46.399
But this is still local and stuck in my computer.

00:05:46.399 --> 00:05:50.399
A link would make it a lot easier to share with learners.

00:05:50.399 --> 00:05:53.040
So how do we start sharing?

00:05:53.040 --> 00:05:59.920
First, we need a web server, which is basically a big computer in the clouds and a hat tip

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:03.519
to Heather Nolas for that analogy.

00:06:03.519 --> 00:06:09.200
And for this webinar, we're going to use a web server provided by Netlify.

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:13.399
So we're going to drag and drop that project folder into Netlify.

00:06:13.399 --> 00:06:16.200
And this is going to put our web page online.

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:22.799
So Allison, let's go ahead and do our first drag and drop.

00:06:22.799 --> 00:06:23.799
Happy to, Desiree.

00:06:23.799 --> 00:06:35.720
So I open up my browser, go to app.netlify.com forward slash drop.

00:06:35.720 --> 00:06:41.000
And I type very slow.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:46.359
And then I'm going to see that little box where it says drag and drop your site folder

00:06:46.359 --> 00:06:47.359
here.

00:06:47.359 --> 00:06:53.000
I'm going to take that lab 2 folder and drag it right into that box.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.239
You can see Netlify things for a second.

00:06:55.239 --> 00:06:56.799
And now my site is live.

00:06:56.799 --> 00:07:02.720
And it gives me a nice random link, friendly Borg, that I can now share with whomever I

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:03.720
choose.

00:07:03.720 --> 00:07:04.720
Hooray.

00:07:04.720 --> 00:07:05.720
All right.

00:07:05.720 --> 00:07:06.720
Hooray.

00:07:06.720 --> 00:07:09.720
We have deployed to Netlify.

00:07:09.720 --> 00:07:12.519
But just as a quick summary of what happened.

00:07:12.519 --> 00:07:14.640
So we started with an R Markdown file.

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:16.600
And it was named index.

00:07:16.600 --> 00:07:22.959
We knit this to convert it to Internet ready HTML file.

00:07:22.959 --> 00:07:23.959
That looked great.

00:07:23.959 --> 00:07:26.959
But it still only lived locally in our R project folder.

00:07:26.959 --> 00:07:33.839
So we had to drag and drop it into Netlify, which deployed our page and generated a link.

00:07:33.839 --> 00:07:34.839
Woohoo.

00:07:34.839 --> 00:07:35.839
Okay.

00:07:35.839 --> 00:07:39.200
But this is just one R Markdown file.

00:07:39.200 --> 00:07:44.160
And we want to be able to share many R Markdown files.

00:07:44.160 --> 00:07:48.959
So we're going to hike Markdown Mountain today.

00:07:48.959 --> 00:07:53.679
And our goal for the rest of this webinar is to show you four R Markdown tools that

00:07:53.679 --> 00:07:59.920
are for turning a collection of R Markdowns into a website.

00:07:59.920 --> 00:08:03.200
And we're going to start with the classic R Markdown site.

00:08:03.200 --> 00:08:07.920
So to make one, you just need the R Markdown package installed, which is already done for

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:11.160
you if you use RStudio.

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:15.239
And here's an R Markdown site for a course about data visualization.

00:08:15.239 --> 00:08:16.239
This is just a screenshot.

00:08:16.239 --> 00:08:18.480
But you can go to the link above it.

00:08:18.480 --> 00:08:23.679
And actually, the MoMA lab that we just turned into a webpage was one of the labs from this

00:08:23.679 --> 00:08:24.679
course.

00:08:24.679 --> 00:08:29.040
Now, this course website is a place to share all of those labs.

00:08:29.040 --> 00:08:35.760
And the biggest addition that we see here is a top navigation bar.

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:40.520
Which allows us to link to other webpages, including ones made with R Markdown, like

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:43.719
this page with slides and readings.

00:08:43.719 --> 00:08:48.559
Or other websites, like this one here, which goes to a learning management system.

00:08:48.559 --> 00:08:50.479
All right.

00:08:50.479 --> 00:08:54.559
So let's build a minimal R Markdown site of our own.

00:08:54.559 --> 00:08:58.359
Imagine that this box on the left is a list of files that are inside of our R project

00:08:58.359 --> 00:09:00.880
folder.

00:09:00.880 --> 00:09:05.880
And to knit all of these pages into our R Markdown site, you can mouse over to the build

00:09:05.880 --> 00:09:10.559
tab in RStudio and then click build website.

00:09:10.559 --> 00:09:15.880
And after we've done that, we see that it's added a new folder called underscore site.

00:09:15.880 --> 00:09:21.119
And that's where all of our HTML files live.

00:09:21.119 --> 00:09:24.559
And then we can also see the site we just built locally.

00:09:24.559 --> 00:09:29.679
We have a nav bar, a theme, and in this case, even a dropdown menu.

00:09:29.679 --> 00:09:34.039
So let's look under the hood at some of these files.

00:09:34.039 --> 00:09:37.359
And we'll start with index.RMD.

00:09:37.359 --> 00:09:42.919
Index is a special file name in any website, because it always becomes the home page.

00:09:42.919 --> 00:09:47.599
So if each of our R Markdown files in our site was a hot air balloon here, index would

00:09:47.599 --> 00:09:51.000
be the first one you see.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:55.880
And if we take a peek inside index.RMD, we actually don't see anything very special.

00:09:56.280 --> 00:10:01.400
In fact, you can actually take any existing R Markdown document that you already have,

00:10:01.400 --> 00:10:07.320
rename it index, and turn it into your site's home page.

00:10:07.320 --> 00:10:10.559
The next file is underscore site.yaml.

00:10:10.559 --> 00:10:11.559
And this is new.

00:10:11.559 --> 00:10:16.039
So this file is in charge of tying all of the pages together.

00:10:16.039 --> 00:10:19.359
And it's a site configuration file written in YAML.

00:10:19.359 --> 00:10:23.320
And let's take a look inside of that.

00:10:23.320 --> 00:10:29.559
So the first thing you may notice is that this is a YAML file, so there are no fences.

00:10:29.559 --> 00:10:32.119
It's just a list of keys and values.

00:10:32.119 --> 00:10:35.119
And the first key that we see is nav bar.

00:10:35.119 --> 00:10:40.479
And this is what lets you build your site's navigation.

00:10:40.479 --> 00:10:44.679
There's a key for title in this site.yaml.

00:10:44.679 --> 00:10:49.679
And whether we want our links to be on the left, but you could also put them on the right.

00:10:49.679 --> 00:10:55.799
And if we want links listed in a dropdown menu, we can do that too from this file.

00:10:55.799 --> 00:11:00.960
And for all the pages you link to in your nav bar, there's a key called href that needs

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:06.799
to point to an HTML file, even though you're using R Markdown files as your source.

00:11:06.799 --> 00:11:10.400
You need to make sure that it's always going to an HTML file.

00:11:10.400 --> 00:11:23.440
And finally, we can set up a theme that will apply to all of the pages throughout our site.

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:28.359
And as for other R Markdown pages, there's nothing special about them either.

00:11:28.359 --> 00:11:33.320
As long as you link to a page in your underscore site YAML, you can take any existing R Markdown

00:11:33.320 --> 00:11:37.880
file and turn it into a page in your site.

00:11:37.880 --> 00:11:40.280
So a quiz, Allison.

00:11:40.280 --> 00:11:44.440
Here is a page that's a lab page in our website.

00:11:44.440 --> 00:11:47.400
What do you think the YAML for this lab page looks like?

00:11:47.400 --> 00:11:49.559
Oh, good question.

00:11:49.559 --> 00:11:58.359
I think that this YAML has table of contents, TOC, as one of the keys that's set to true.

00:11:58.359 --> 00:12:00.080
And I see it's floating off to the left.

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:04.239
So I think TOC underscore float is also set to true.

00:12:04.239 --> 00:12:08.039
And I see my favorite code download key.

00:12:08.039 --> 00:12:12.200
So code underscore download, I believe, is true also, which allows you to click on that

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:17.359
nice little download RMD button, and somebody can download your source RMD file.

00:12:17.359 --> 00:12:20.840
Okay, Allison, good job.

00:12:20.840 --> 00:12:22.960
That's exactly what we see.

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:26.359
You can set the YAML for each page if you want.

00:12:26.359 --> 00:12:30.239
It doesn't only have to be done in the underscore site YAML file.

00:12:30.239 --> 00:12:35.039
And if you want the output options to apply to every single page, that's when you would

00:12:35.039 --> 00:12:39.960
choose to put it in the underscore site YAML file as opposed to the individual page.

00:12:39.960 --> 00:12:41.799
But okay.

00:12:41.799 --> 00:12:45.440
So finally, we are ready to share our Markdown site.

00:12:45.440 --> 00:12:48.419
And we'll do this the same way as we did before.

00:12:48.419 --> 00:12:54.380
As a reminder, all of our HTML website-ready pages are stored in this underscore site folder.

00:12:54.380 --> 00:12:58.400
So this is the only folder that we need to drag and drop.

00:12:58.400 --> 00:13:01.119
So Allison, can you take it away again?

00:13:01.119 --> 00:13:02.919
I will.

00:13:02.919 --> 00:13:08.080
So here we're back at app.netlify.com forward slash drop, and we're dropping that underscore

00:13:08.080 --> 00:13:12.359
site folder right in.

00:13:12.359 --> 00:13:18.080
And we're able to get a link, Hardcore Goldwasser.

00:13:18.080 --> 00:13:19.080
Great name.

00:13:19.080 --> 00:13:20.080
Website.

00:13:20.080 --> 00:13:21.080
Okay.

00:13:21.080 --> 00:13:25.440
Thank you.

00:13:25.440 --> 00:13:29.900
So one thing you may have noticed with what Allison just showed you is that there's a

00:13:29.900 --> 00:13:34.960
note from Netlify, and it says, unclaimed sites are deleted after 24 hours.

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:39.440
So we have to actually create an account with Netlify to keep our site online permanently.

00:13:39.440 --> 00:13:43.440
So let's actually go back to Netlify and do that.

00:13:43.440 --> 00:13:44.440
Okay.

00:13:44.440 --> 00:13:51.359
So we click on that little sign up for Netlify button, and you can sign up with an existing

00:13:51.359 --> 00:13:54.520
version control account like GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket.

00:13:54.599 --> 00:13:58.559
So if you have one, I encourage you to use those to sign into Netlify, because that'll

00:13:58.559 --> 00:14:03.039
make your life easier.

00:14:03.039 --> 00:14:06.400
And today we're going to actually sign up with an email address.

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:15.559
So Desiree's entering an email address, signing up for an account with Netlify.

00:14:15.559 --> 00:14:28.119
She's waiting on instructions for how to verify her account.

00:14:28.119 --> 00:14:31.280
And we have it.

00:14:31.280 --> 00:14:41.359
And we will be able to own, was it Hardcore Goldwasser forever?

00:14:41.359 --> 00:14:48.239
So now it's part of her team on her Netlify account, and your silly named link is now

00:14:48.239 --> 00:14:49.840
here to stay.

00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:54.080
All right, great.

00:14:54.080 --> 00:14:56.359
Okay.

00:14:56.359 --> 00:15:02.859
But after I've deployed my site, what happens if I decide that I want to make a change?

00:15:02.859 --> 00:15:09.520
So let's say, for example, looking at the YAML file on the left side, say that I want

00:15:09.520 --> 00:15:13.320
to change my theme to something named United.

00:15:13.320 --> 00:15:19.880
So once I make that change, I need to remember to rebuild my website.

00:15:19.880 --> 00:15:24.840
And then I need to be able to drag and drop again.

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:27.840
So let's see what that process looks like.

00:15:27.840 --> 00:15:35.919
Sorry, my mouse has gone missing.

00:15:35.919 --> 00:15:36.919
There we go.

00:15:36.919 --> 00:15:37.919
Okay.

00:15:37.919 --> 00:15:38.919
Okay.

00:15:39.320 --> 00:15:40.320
Okay.

00:15:40.320 --> 00:15:46.440
So once we've rebuilt our site with the changes that we want, we can just use that underscore

00:15:46.440 --> 00:15:52.000
site folder again, but we have to go into deploys in our Netlify UI.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:55.119
And then you see this little box, need to update your site, drag and drop your site

00:15:55.119 --> 00:15:56.119
folder here.

00:15:56.119 --> 00:16:00.979
So this means that we get to keep that link, the Hardcore Goldwasser link, and update the

00:16:00.979 --> 00:16:04.299
same link with our new content.

00:16:04.299 --> 00:16:09.599
So if we drag and drop it again, it takes a second to think, and it republishes.

00:16:09.599 --> 00:16:13.539
So now if we click on the link, we can see that our new theme, the United theme, has

00:16:13.539 --> 00:16:14.539
been applied.

00:16:14.539 --> 00:16:17.820
So it looks a little bit different, but the link is the same.

00:16:17.820 --> 00:16:21.700
Great.

00:16:21.700 --> 00:16:25.260
So now you know how to build and update our Markdown sites.

00:16:25.260 --> 00:16:29.780
And before we move on to the next tool, I just want to highlight some good and bad points

00:16:29.780 --> 00:16:32.640
to take away about using this tool for a course.

00:16:32.640 --> 00:16:35.880
So some really great things is that the source stays the same.

00:16:35.880 --> 00:16:40.359
You can use a lot of your existing documents and just plop them right in without having

00:16:40.359 --> 00:16:41.760
to change much at all.

00:16:41.760 --> 00:16:45.400
And another really great thing is that you have these built-in themes you can take advantage

00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:48.960
of to kind of give your site a makeover easily.

00:16:48.960 --> 00:16:55.299
A bad thing about our Markdown sites is that as you start to add many different pages,

00:16:55.299 --> 00:16:59.219
your directory can get really, really full because our Markdown sites do not allow you

00:16:59.219 --> 00:17:02.919
to organize pages and our Markdown documents into subfolders.

00:17:02.919 --> 00:17:05.599
So that's just one thing to kind of keep in mind.

00:17:05.599 --> 00:17:11.640
But with that, let's go ahead and move on to our next tool, which is Distill.

00:17:11.640 --> 00:17:16.680
So our next stop on Markdown Mountain is a Distill website, and you'll have to install

00:17:16.680 --> 00:17:21.439
the Distill package before you can use it.

00:17:21.439 --> 00:17:27.680
And I just want to give you a quick tour of the Distill website.

00:17:27.680 --> 00:17:32.339
So let's go ahead and press play here.

00:17:32.339 --> 00:17:37.500
And the style of a Distill site is actually not very easy to change without CSS, but it

00:17:37.500 --> 00:17:39.579
looks pretty slick out of the box.

00:17:39.579 --> 00:17:44.780
So you can think of Distill as being a little bit like the nerdier sibling of an R Markdown

00:17:44.780 --> 00:17:45.780
site.

00:17:45.780 --> 00:17:49.780
It's built for much more technical and scientific communication.

00:17:49.780 --> 00:18:03.319
So for example, there is a way to list multiple authors and their affiliations.

00:18:03.319 --> 00:18:08.380
You can also include footers and asides in your Distill pages.

00:18:08.380 --> 00:18:15.479
And there's this really nice way to display reuse licenses for your educational content.

00:18:15.479 --> 00:18:18.800
So those are some of the features in a Distill website that come out of the box.

00:18:18.819 --> 00:18:22.099
And so now let's build a minimal Distill site of our own.

00:18:22.099 --> 00:18:27.060
And just like we did with the R Markdown site, we're going to use the Build tab to knit some

00:18:27.060 --> 00:18:29.979
files that are in our project directory.

00:18:29.979 --> 00:18:34.699
And once we do that, it's going to create a folder, again, called underscore site that's

00:18:34.699 --> 00:18:38.780
going to house our HTML files.

00:18:38.780 --> 00:18:43.839
Here is what our minimal Distill site is going to look like.

00:18:43.839 --> 00:18:48.660
And just to point out, we can also add, we can have a description, we can have those

00:18:48.660 --> 00:18:53.660
multiple authors, we can still retain that drop down menu that we also had in R Markdown

00:18:53.660 --> 00:18:54.660
sites.

00:18:54.660 --> 00:18:59.900
So let's look at some of these files a little bit more closely, starting with the index

00:18:59.900 --> 00:19:00.900
page.

00:19:00.900 --> 00:19:04.800
Again, this is going to be our homepage in a Distill website.

00:19:04.800 --> 00:19:09.400
And any existing R Markdown document that you have will do.

00:19:09.400 --> 00:19:13.439
There's just one addition we need to make inside of this file.

00:19:13.439 --> 00:19:19.540
And that is that in the YAML of the index file, we need to be able to add this line

00:19:19.540 --> 00:19:23.459
site, Distill, Distill website.

00:19:23.459 --> 00:19:30.400
And it's also nice to include a title and a short description, but not necessary.

00:19:30.400 --> 00:19:33.880
And then we also have an underscore site YAML file.

00:19:33.880 --> 00:19:36.239
This is still going to be our site configuration.

00:19:36.239 --> 00:19:42.040
So this should also sound a bit familiar.

00:19:42.040 --> 00:19:46.640
And the YAML navbar keys here are similar to what we used in R Markdown sites with one

00:19:46.640 --> 00:19:57.359
important change, the output must specify that this is going to be a Distill article.

00:19:57.359 --> 00:20:02.880
And there's one more thing I need to tell you about Distill websites.

00:20:02.880 --> 00:20:08.800
You can make part of your Distill website into a blog, which looks like this.

00:20:08.800 --> 00:20:12.920
So essentially, you can have a single page made up of clickable posts.

00:20:12.920 --> 00:20:17.239
And each post itself is its own page, and it doesn't need to be built into the navigation

00:20:17.239 --> 00:20:24.079
bar the way that other parts of the R Markdown sites need to be or like Distill sites need

00:20:24.079 --> 00:20:25.199
to be.

00:20:25.199 --> 00:20:28.880
And this can be useful in a classroom setting, just if you want to post different things

00:20:28.880 --> 00:20:34.800
like announcements, and kind of a running list sort of way.

00:20:34.800 --> 00:20:39.920
So in order to create a blog-like page, we first need to create what's called a listing

00:20:39.920 --> 00:20:41.359
page.

00:20:41.359 --> 00:20:47.119
And this is an R Markdown document whose only job is to have a title and then a listing

00:20:47.119 --> 00:20:49.199
YAML key and value.

00:20:49.199 --> 00:20:54.680
And we're going to call our listing page schedule.

00:20:54.680 --> 00:21:00.800
And then we have to remember to link this listing page to the navigation bar within

00:21:00.800 --> 00:21:01.800
site YAML.

00:21:01.800 --> 00:21:08.319
And once we've done that, then we're ready to make some blog posts.

00:21:08.319 --> 00:21:14.280
So the most straightforward way to create a post is to run the code distill create post,

00:21:14.280 --> 00:21:17.699
and then within the parentheses, you put the title of your post.

00:21:17.699 --> 00:21:22.880
And this is automatically going to create a new folder called posts with a subdirectory

00:21:22.880 --> 00:21:24.420
for your post.

00:21:24.420 --> 00:21:29.000
And it will also trigger a little window to open with your R Markdown file ready for you

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:30.520
to edit.

00:21:30.520 --> 00:21:34.040
You can rinse and repeat this process, creating as many new posts as you'd like.

00:21:34.040 --> 00:21:37.640
So let's go ahead and just look inside one of those post files.

00:21:37.640 --> 00:21:41.199
On the left here, you can see what I mean when I said that it creates a little subdirectory

00:21:41.199 --> 00:21:44.219
for your post underneath the posts folder.

00:21:44.219 --> 00:21:45.219
And all of this is created for you.

00:21:45.219 --> 00:21:48.479
So you don't really have to worry too much about remembering the order here.

00:21:48.479 --> 00:21:54.640
But if we look inside of the post itself, we see that the YAML is already automatically

00:21:54.640 --> 00:21:57.880
populated for us with the information that we need.

00:21:57.880 --> 00:22:02.599
We can edit it if we need to, like change the date or the title.

00:22:02.599 --> 00:22:06.040
And the only downside here is that once we're done creating our post, we have to remember

00:22:06.040 --> 00:22:09.160
to knit this post individually.

00:22:09.160 --> 00:22:14.939
If you don't knit it on its own, then it won't show up on your listing page.

00:22:14.939 --> 00:22:20.079
So once we've created all of our posts, we can then remember to build our website one

00:22:20.079 --> 00:22:27.760
last time so that the listing page will be updated with any posts that we've created.

00:22:28.640 --> 00:22:33.239
And here, for example, is what our very minimal blog listing page looks like.

00:22:33.239 --> 00:22:37.439
So on the left, you see what the listing page is, and then you can click on to any of those

00:22:37.439 --> 00:22:43.680
individual links to see what the post looks like.

00:22:43.680 --> 00:22:48.640
And just as before, once we're ready to share, we can use our old drag and drop method.

00:22:48.640 --> 00:22:55.119
So we'll take the underscore site folder and drag that in to Netlify, just as we did with

00:22:55.119 --> 00:22:59.520
our Markdown sites.

00:22:59.520 --> 00:23:04.160
So with that, we've covered two of our Markdown tools, and there's just a couple points I

00:23:04.160 --> 00:23:08.420
want to highlight about Distill before we move on to the next tool.

00:23:08.420 --> 00:23:13.280
Really nice things about Distill are that you have these really great design features

00:23:13.280 --> 00:23:14.280
out of the box.

00:23:14.280 --> 00:23:15.280
You have two content flavors.

00:23:15.280 --> 00:23:20.000
You can have a regular page, but you can also have this blog-like page, which kind of just

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:24.160
lets you show some more chronological content.

00:23:24.199 --> 00:23:29.319
One bad thing about Distill, it's just pretty annoying, I guess, to have to remember to

00:23:29.319 --> 00:23:35.920
knit each individual post one by one, if you would like to take advantage of the blog feature.

00:23:35.920 --> 00:23:40.319
But the good thing there, at least, is that you don't have to do anything manual to make

00:23:40.319 --> 00:23:44.800
sure that your posts get on that listing page we created.

00:23:44.800 --> 00:23:52.520
Okay, so now for the rest of the tools, Allison will be our guide for our Ascent Markdown

00:23:52.520 --> 00:23:57.640
Mountain, and we have two more tools to go.

00:23:57.640 --> 00:23:59.599
Thank you, Jessica.

00:23:59.599 --> 00:24:06.000
So I'm going to describe Bookdown now, which is another R package that you need to install

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:09.439
before being able to use it.

00:24:09.439 --> 00:24:15.000
And as the package name suggests, Bookdown is a way to build books with R Markdown, and

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:21.040
you can use it to build an online book with a table of contents, chapters, in fact, as

00:24:21.040 --> 00:24:26.280
many chapters as you want, and lots of bells and whistles that we won't be able to cover

00:24:26.280 --> 00:24:27.280
today.

00:24:27.280 --> 00:24:32.680
But they're all actually covered in the Bookdown book, which you can see here, and it also

00:24:32.680 --> 00:24:35.239
happens to be a Bookdown book itself.

00:24:35.239 --> 00:24:42.000
So you can see that we have a website here that looks a little bit different than the

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:45.839
R Markdown and Distill sites that Desiree just showed us.

00:24:45.839 --> 00:24:50.239
Instead of having that top navigation bar that allowed us to navigate and find the different

00:24:50.239 --> 00:24:55.119
pages on our site, now we have this table of contents over here in this kind of left

00:24:55.119 --> 00:24:56.119
sidebar.

00:24:56.119 --> 00:25:01.400
So when I click on that little hamburger menu, I can see my table of contents going up and

00:25:01.400 --> 00:25:03.040
down, and I can scroll it.

00:25:03.040 --> 00:25:07.000
It's a very long table of contents, but you can see that I have a lot of materials in

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:11.000
here, and I can click around to any of these, and you can see that the right pane shows

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:14.719
me the content of that page as I click around.

00:25:14.719 --> 00:25:20.400
So here in a Bookdown book, each of these chapters is actually an R Markdown file, and

00:25:20.400 --> 00:25:24.680
when I click on it, I'm able to see the content, but I can still access the entire table of

00:25:24.680 --> 00:25:25.680
contents here.

00:25:25.680 --> 00:25:29.920
And you can imagine that if you had this many documents in an R Markdown or a Distill site,

00:25:29.920 --> 00:25:34.359
you would have had to build them usually manually into some kind of top navigation bar, and

00:25:34.359 --> 00:25:38.579
you just don't have that much real estate going across the top as you do with this kind

00:25:38.579 --> 00:25:39.579
of layout.

00:25:39.579 --> 00:25:43.640
So that's one of the reasons that Bookdown is really popular for educators.

00:25:43.640 --> 00:25:48.640
Bookdown also comes with search built in, so you're able to search the entire book.

00:25:48.640 --> 00:25:57.199
So this is also another nice feature that allows you to leverage your content.

00:25:57.199 --> 00:26:02.280
So here's an example of a much shorter Bookdown book that I built to show you for a demonstration.

00:26:02.280 --> 00:26:05.479
So we can give you a quick tour of the files that go into it.

00:26:05.479 --> 00:26:10.359
So this book has three labs from a course I taught on data visualization.

00:26:10.359 --> 00:26:13.479
The first one is about Nathan's hot dog eating contest.

00:26:13.479 --> 00:26:18.040
The second one is the one that Desiree just showed you at the MoMA Museum tour.

00:26:18.040 --> 00:26:24.000
And the third one was a lesson teaching about colors with ggplot using data about children's

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:27.439
production of animal sounds.

00:26:27.439 --> 00:26:30.640
So the files in this book project here are on the left.

00:26:30.640 --> 00:26:36.760
So you can see that I have a few R Markdown files, I have a YAML file, it's an R project,

00:26:36.760 --> 00:26:41.439
I have some folders, and I have a very important folder called underscore book.

00:26:41.439 --> 00:26:46.839
Now Desiree, do you happen to remember what the output folder was for R Markdown and Distill Sites?

00:26:46.839 --> 00:26:50.319
Yes, I do. It was underscore site.

00:26:50.319 --> 00:26:51.319
Yes.

00:26:51.319 --> 00:26:56.800
So with a Bookdown book, now our book is in underscore book.

00:26:56.800 --> 00:27:01.560
So when I have all of these files that you see over here in the left pane, when I have

00:27:01.560 --> 00:27:07.599
all those in a directory for an R project, and I mouse over to my build tab, and I click

00:27:07.599 --> 00:27:12.719
on that build book icon, it creates a new folder called underscore book, and that's

00:27:12.719 --> 00:27:15.079
where my book now lives locally.

00:27:15.079 --> 00:27:18.479
So I'm going to show you inside some of those files now.

00:27:18.479 --> 00:27:21.699
So let's take a look first at index.rmv.

00:27:21.699 --> 00:27:26.400
So Desiree described this as the homepage for your other R Markdown sites, and it's

00:27:26.400 --> 00:27:28.680
actually the homepage also for Bookdown.

00:27:28.680 --> 00:27:32.760
It also happens to turn into your first chapter.

00:27:32.760 --> 00:27:35.839
So if you take a look inside, it looks pretty familiar.

00:27:35.839 --> 00:27:37.280
There's YAML at the top.

00:27:37.280 --> 00:27:40.599
We have a title, a subtitle, an author.

00:27:40.599 --> 00:27:45.800
We also have two new YAML keys on the bottom, and these are critical for building a Bookdown book.

00:27:45.800 --> 00:27:47.800
They are site and output.

00:27:47.800 --> 00:27:53.520
So both of those are necessary for building an HTML book like the one we're building now.

00:27:53.520 --> 00:27:58.280
And then the rest of this file, everything underneath the YAML, can be a regular R Markdown file.

00:27:58.280 --> 00:28:02.640
It just also happens to turn into chapter one.

00:28:02.640 --> 00:28:06.839
So like with our other sites, we also have a separate file, too.

00:28:06.839 --> 00:28:15.439
So in the R Markdown and the sites that Desiree demonstrated, you had underscore site.yaml file.

00:28:15.439 --> 00:28:19.359
And in Bookdown, it's an underscore bookdown.yaml file.

00:28:19.359 --> 00:28:27.920
And this file works in concert with the index.rmv file to guide how all of our chapters fit together.

00:28:27.920 --> 00:28:33.719
So I'm going to recommend that your underscore bookdown.yaml file is pretty sparse.

00:28:33.719 --> 00:28:38.680
The main key that I recommend using for this YAML file is new session, and I recommend

00:28:38.680 --> 00:28:40.199
that you set it to true.

00:28:40.199 --> 00:28:45.880
This means that each of your R Markdown chapters is knit in a separate session.

00:28:45.880 --> 00:28:50.319
This will make your life easier and will make it easier for you to troubleshoot when you're

00:28:50.319 --> 00:28:52.719
knitting your book, building your book.

00:28:52.719 --> 00:28:57.359
Any of the errors that you see will be a lot easier to debug if each of the chapters is

00:28:57.359 --> 00:29:00.000
totally independent.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:04.599
You might notice that my chapter files here on the left are now named with numbers as

00:29:04.599 --> 00:29:05.599
prefixes.

00:29:05.599 --> 00:29:10.560
So I have 01 hot dogs, 02 moma, and 03 meow.

00:29:10.560 --> 00:29:17.520
You can use the bookdown.yaml file to instead list the order of your R Markdown chapters.

00:29:17.520 --> 00:29:23.000
So before, it was using the numbered chapters to determine the order that the book got built.

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:28.560
You can also take away those numbers from the names of the files and use the bookdown.yaml

00:29:28.560 --> 00:29:32.560
to determine the order of the chapters as they are presented to you.

00:29:32.560 --> 00:29:38.680
So that's another way that you can use this underscore bookdown.yaml file.

00:29:38.680 --> 00:29:44.199
And the chapters themselves, I have three of them here in addition to the index.rmd.

00:29:44.199 --> 00:29:49.079
Those are each separate R Markdown files, but they're with one major change.

00:29:49.079 --> 00:29:54.280
And that is that each of these chapters has to begin with a level one markdown header.

00:29:54.280 --> 00:29:57.739
So here you see hashtag momamuseumtour.

00:29:57.739 --> 00:30:00.560
Each of these chapters has to start with that.

00:30:00.560 --> 00:30:05.800
And so that means that none of your chapters in a bookdown book can have its own yaml.

00:30:05.800 --> 00:30:10.040
And so this is probably the biggest problem for if you're going to be trying to convert

00:30:10.040 --> 00:30:11.839
existing material into bookdown.

00:30:11.839 --> 00:30:16.640
It means that you're going to have to remove the yaml from each individual R Markdown file

00:30:16.640 --> 00:30:18.119
that will go into a chapter.

00:30:18.160 --> 00:30:24.199
So each chapter has to start with a level one markdown header and can't have its own yaml.

00:30:24.199 --> 00:30:29.640
They actually put in the yaml from the index.rmd.

00:30:29.640 --> 00:30:33.760
And so this gives you a little bit of an overview of what bookdown is doing.

00:30:33.760 --> 00:30:39.119
So what you make is you make these separate R Markdown files for each chapter.

00:30:39.119 --> 00:30:44.540
So here we have index.rmd and then another rmd and another rmd and each of those begins

00:30:44.540 --> 00:30:47.079
with that level one chapter heading.

00:30:47.079 --> 00:30:49.599
Those are all your separate R Markdown files.

00:30:49.599 --> 00:30:53.880
And remember that index.rmd is a special one that also includes a yaml.

00:30:53.880 --> 00:30:59.959
What bookdown does when you have this new session true in the bookdown yaml is that

00:30:59.959 --> 00:31:06.199
it emits these R Markdown files in a separate page.

00:31:06.199 --> 00:31:08.359
So each of those is now independent.

00:31:08.359 --> 00:31:11.640
But how do we get to the point where we're seeing them all together?

00:31:11.640 --> 00:31:18.800
Bookdown merges them and gives us the nice interactive online navigable book that we

00:31:18.800 --> 00:31:23.099
see when we build the book.

00:31:23.099 --> 00:31:26.839
So how do we share the book once it's actually written and built?

00:31:26.839 --> 00:31:30.500
We know our HTML files live in that underscore book folder.

00:31:30.500 --> 00:31:33.800
So this should seem like old hat to you now.

00:31:33.800 --> 00:31:41.400
What I would do is go to app.netlify.com forward slash drop and I can drop that underscore

00:31:41.400 --> 00:31:46.800
book folder into the same spot and that would give me a link.

00:31:46.800 --> 00:31:49.760
But you might have noticed that some of those random domain names are hard to remember and

00:31:49.760 --> 00:31:50.760
keep track of.

00:31:50.760 --> 00:31:55.959
I believe one that Desiree was working with was called Hardcore Goldwasser.

00:31:55.959 --> 00:32:00.520
It's good for flying under the radar but they're probably not great for learners and they're

00:32:00.520 --> 00:32:02.760
probably not easy for you to share.

00:32:02.760 --> 00:32:07.280
So we can update the domain on netlify.com to make the link easier to share with other

00:32:07.280 --> 00:32:08.280
people.

00:32:08.280 --> 00:32:12.520
So in this example, our random domain was Stoic Babbage.

00:32:12.520 --> 00:32:17.560
So if you go into the Deploys tab on Netlify once you've made your account, you can see

00:32:17.560 --> 00:32:23.239
that that's my default subdomain and if I click on Options, Edit Site Name, then I can

00:32:23.239 --> 00:32:24.239
change it.

00:32:24.239 --> 00:32:30.239
So here I'm going to change it to datavis-book, which amazingly was not taken.

00:32:30.239 --> 00:32:38.439
So now I have the domain datavis-book.netlify.com and you can see it takes a second but it has

00:32:38.439 --> 00:32:39.520
already deployed.

00:32:39.520 --> 00:32:44.560
The new link works right away and now because I have an account with Netlify and I've changed

00:32:44.560 --> 00:32:46.680
that domain, that's my domain forever.

00:32:46.680 --> 00:32:54.520
I can keep that and I can always update that as well the way we showed you earlier.

00:32:54.520 --> 00:32:58.560
So the best part about Bookdown is that I think it's hard to get lost in a Bookdown

00:32:58.560 --> 00:32:59.560
book.

00:33:00.239 --> 00:33:03.880
By default, you think it's going to be long because you have this big table of contents

00:33:03.880 --> 00:33:04.880
on the left side.

00:33:04.880 --> 00:33:06.640
So that works in your favor.

00:33:06.640 --> 00:33:10.880
People are used to being able to scroll up and down vertically in that table of contents

00:33:10.880 --> 00:33:12.959
and the search functions help as well.

00:33:12.959 --> 00:33:16.079
And so since you have more real estate in the table of contents vertically, you can

00:33:16.079 --> 00:33:17.880
also add a lot more content in.

00:33:17.880 --> 00:33:22.599
So it may be easier when you have longer form content for teaching as opposed to an R Markdown

00:33:22.599 --> 00:33:27.959
site or a Distill site where you have to kind of manually build up that site navigation.

00:33:27.959 --> 00:33:33.160
The hard parts of Bookdown are that if you're converting existing R Markdown files over

00:33:33.160 --> 00:33:38.479
to this new format, you're going to have to do some work to be able to remove those YAMLs

00:33:38.479 --> 00:33:44.680
from your individual files and start them all with those level one chapter headers.

00:33:44.680 --> 00:33:50.920
You may also need to rename your files and you also still don't get to have subfolders.

00:33:50.920 --> 00:33:54.680
So you're still going to have all your R Markdown files in one directory.

00:33:54.680 --> 00:34:02.400
And so once you get a certain number of these, it can pretty quickly feel fairly messy.

00:34:02.400 --> 00:34:05.959
So Desiree, we have made it to the summit, which is Blockdown.

00:34:05.959 --> 00:34:06.959
We have!

00:34:06.959 --> 00:34:07.959
Yes!

00:34:07.959 --> 00:34:08.959
Hooray!

00:34:08.959 --> 00:34:11.959
Hooray indeed.

00:34:11.959 --> 00:34:16.879
So Blockdown is a great package for building custom and unique websites with R Markdown,

00:34:16.879 --> 00:34:19.000
but it is not for the faint of heart.

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:23.760
It is also probably not the best choice for you to adopt on complete short notice because

00:34:23.840 --> 00:34:25.479
there is a lot to learn.

00:34:25.479 --> 00:34:28.760
But I wanted to make sure that you know about it in case you've already tried the tools

00:34:28.760 --> 00:34:29.760
that we've just covered.

00:34:29.760 --> 00:34:33.959
So if you've already tried R Markdown sites, Distill sites, or Bookdown and you're still

00:34:33.959 --> 00:34:38.719
not quite satisfied with the options and you want something highly customizable, then you

00:34:38.719 --> 00:34:41.000
may want to look at Blockdown.

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:45.239
Or for other folks who have a little bit more time to prep, if you're looking at a fall

00:34:45.239 --> 00:34:52.600
or a winter quarter class for next year, you could think about making a website using Blockdown.

00:34:52.600 --> 00:34:54.760
So what is Blockdown?

00:34:54.760 --> 00:34:59.840
It's an R package that helps you build a website using a generator called Hugo.

00:34:59.840 --> 00:35:05.840
And the package itself lets you use the RStudio IDE to build your site and to use R Markdown

00:35:05.840 --> 00:35:09.520
content to make your site.

00:35:09.520 --> 00:35:17.080
So one of the best and worst things about Hugo is that you now have access to over 100 Hugo

00:35:17.080 --> 00:35:18.760
themes to choose from.

00:35:18.760 --> 00:35:22.040
So you can get really creative with Hugo.

00:35:22.479 --> 00:35:27.000
So you may have felt like when you were looking at Bookdown sites or Distill or R Markdown

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:31.120
sites, you've probably seen a lot of sites that look just like those.

00:35:31.120 --> 00:35:32.479
And there's some benefits to that.

00:35:32.479 --> 00:35:35.560
I don't think there's anything wrong with using a default site.

00:35:35.560 --> 00:35:40.040
But a lot of people want to go a little bit further and they have specialized needs that

00:35:40.040 --> 00:35:43.100
require specialized solutions.

00:35:43.100 --> 00:35:49.719
But it's also easy to get very overwhelmed by the choices of Hugo themes.

00:35:50.479 --> 00:35:56.159
For my own course websites and when I teach, my favorite theme to use is the Hugo academic

00:35:56.159 --> 00:36:01.399
theme, because it is very well documented and it's very flexible also.

00:36:01.399 --> 00:36:04.919
The theme also has built-in search, which is really nice.

00:36:04.919 --> 00:36:08.439
So here is the documentation theme for academic.

00:36:08.439 --> 00:36:10.120
It's a demonstration site.

00:36:10.120 --> 00:36:14.459
You can see that I have a little search button up at the top.

00:36:14.459 --> 00:36:17.239
And you can see that there's all kinds of different content in here.

00:36:17.239 --> 00:36:20.800
And it's important to remember with Hugo sites, when you look at a demonstration site,

00:36:20.800 --> 00:36:22.179
it's trying to show you everything.

00:36:22.179 --> 00:36:26.719
It's not necessarily showing you the best way to lay out everything.

00:36:26.719 --> 00:36:34.959
So I built a demonstration site for this webinar using the Hugo academic theme and porting

00:36:34.959 --> 00:36:40.439
over my existing content from the course I taught on data visualization, where I had

00:36:40.439 --> 00:36:44.439
that R Markdown site that Desiree actually showed at the very beginning.

00:36:44.439 --> 00:36:49.080
So I converted all of that content over to BlogDown to show you what's possible.

00:36:49.080 --> 00:36:55.679
So here is my BlogDown site, and you can access it at share-blogdown.netlify.com, and you

00:36:55.679 --> 00:36:58.320
can see I have my nice built-in search.

00:36:58.320 --> 00:37:03.239
I have this top nav bar, and you can see I have some nice features, like being able to

00:37:03.239 --> 00:37:09.239
link to my RStudio Cloud, perhaps, or my Piazza, GitHub.

00:37:09.239 --> 00:37:11.280
You can put all those links in one place.

00:37:11.280 --> 00:37:15.560
You can also see that I have some interesting kind of ways to lay out content that are a

00:37:15.560 --> 00:37:20.840
little bit more varied than what we had at our fingertips with R Markdown, Distill, and

00:37:20.840 --> 00:37:23.000
BookDown sites.

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:29.399
Here I've also used blog posts to lay out a schedule, and this was inspired by Meneh

00:37:29.399 --> 00:37:35.360
Chetankaya-Randell's course website, so showing you each of the labs stacked on top of each

00:37:35.360 --> 00:37:36.360
other.

00:37:36.360 --> 00:37:41.760
So here, click on Schedule Lab, the content for that lab.

00:37:41.760 --> 00:37:47.600
You can also see, of course, a section for the syllabus, and finally, some instructors

00:37:47.600 --> 00:37:50.879
with pictures, links, all of the things.

00:37:50.879 --> 00:37:54.919
There's also a resources section here that shows a different kind of layout where you

00:37:54.919 --> 00:38:00.639
can share different materials with users, just another different option that's available

00:38:00.639 --> 00:38:03.699
with the Hugo Academic theme.

00:38:03.699 --> 00:38:08.659
So here, if you remember, I showed you this schedule, and if I clicked on this Lab02,

00:38:08.659 --> 00:38:13.979
the MoMA Museum Tour, that's actually the lab that Desiree started with initially.

00:38:13.979 --> 00:38:16.260
So let me show you what that looks like.

00:38:16.260 --> 00:38:21.899
You would go to that page, and you would see these two here, Lab, and what each of those

00:38:21.899 --> 00:38:25.899
goes to is actually, the lab goes to an R Markdown site.

00:38:25.899 --> 00:38:30.139
So this is housed within my blog down site, but I didn't have to change anything about

00:38:30.139 --> 00:38:31.139
that file.

00:38:31.139 --> 00:38:35.979
I literally just copied and pasted it over into a directory in my blog down site.

00:38:35.979 --> 00:38:41.260
And then I also used ShurEngine slides to make my presentation slides in R Markdown.

00:38:41.260 --> 00:38:46.899
So you can see that I also copied and pasted those directly from my R Markdown site and

00:38:46.899 --> 00:38:49.560
directory in my blog down site.

00:38:49.560 --> 00:38:53.500
And then this allows me to take advantage of one of the best benefits of using blog

00:38:53.500 --> 00:38:59.219
down for teaching, which is that when I use the add-in to build my site, so I use the

00:38:59.219 --> 00:39:06.260
blog down add-in serve site, it creates a folder called underscore public, and that's

00:39:06.260 --> 00:39:10.659
the website that I see, but what it also does under the hood for me is it builds any other

00:39:10.659 --> 00:39:13.899
kind of R Markdown content that I have.

00:39:13.899 --> 00:39:19.540
So I can house my other R Markdown HTML documents in here, as well as my ShurEngine slides.

00:39:19.540 --> 00:39:25.580
I can do it all, and I can build it all with one button, which is really nice.

00:39:25.580 --> 00:39:29.260
So just a quick tour of some of the files in a blog down project.

00:39:29.260 --> 00:39:33.379
The content folder is probably the place that you'll want to dig into the most.

00:39:33.379 --> 00:39:35.459
Your primary R Markdown files will live here.

00:39:35.459 --> 00:39:38.219
You can also use plain Markdown files.

00:39:38.219 --> 00:39:42.340
YAML does depend on the theme that you choose, though, so this means that you'll need to

00:39:42.340 --> 00:39:46.860
change any existing YAML to adapt to your theme, and this is also how you can kind of

00:39:46.860 --> 00:39:48.139
get locked into a theme.

00:39:48.139 --> 00:39:53.260
So once you choose a theme in blog down, it's tough to switch.

00:39:53.260 --> 00:39:57.899
Sometimes I also stash and build other R Markdown documents in the static folder, and

00:39:57.899 --> 00:40:03.620
if you go to the repository associated with my demo site, you can see how I did that to

00:40:03.620 --> 00:40:06.459
deploy my R Markdown labs and my ShurEngine slides.

00:40:06.459 --> 00:40:12.219
So that's just a taste of blog down to give you a flavor for the things that are possible.

00:40:12.219 --> 00:40:15.300
So the good parts of blog down is that you can finally now have subfolders.

00:40:15.300 --> 00:40:19.939
You can have a content folder organization that might help you if you have a lot of different

00:40:19.939 --> 00:40:24.379
things like data, assignments, labs, slides.

00:40:24.379 --> 00:40:29.540
You can also knit anything, so you can have different output formats are possible.

00:40:29.540 --> 00:40:33.179
Blog down also builds on top of book down, so any of the features that are present in

00:40:33.179 --> 00:40:38.379
the book down HTML format are also possible in blog down.

00:40:38.379 --> 00:40:41.739
The bad things, in my experience, are Hugo.

00:40:41.739 --> 00:40:43.540
Hugo is a new dependency that we've added.

00:40:43.540 --> 00:40:48.659
All the other options that we've discussed so far, our Markdown sites, Distill, and Bookdown

00:40:48.659 --> 00:40:53.540
only had an R package that they depended on, but now when you work with blog down,

00:40:53.540 --> 00:40:59.179
you are depending on installing Hugo, which is a language that does have different versions.

00:40:59.179 --> 00:41:00.419
It requires updates.

00:41:00.419 --> 00:41:02.620
There's a bit of maintenance involved.

00:41:02.620 --> 00:41:06.979
There's also a more complex directory structure, so with being able to have subfolders, you

00:41:06.979 --> 00:41:09.739
also gain more complexity as well.

00:41:09.739 --> 00:41:13.959
So I wouldn't necessarily recommend this for short notice, but I do think it's a nice longer

00:41:13.959 --> 00:41:16.300
term solution.

00:41:16.300 --> 00:41:17.820
Some general blog down advice.

00:41:17.820 --> 00:41:23.179
I do not recommend that you update Hugo during your course if you're using blog down.

00:41:23.179 --> 00:41:29.260
I also do not recommend that you update your Hugo theme during your course, and I also

00:41:29.260 --> 00:41:36.179
just generally recommend don't update anything during your course based on personal experience.

